        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-04T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-04T06:00:00-05:00" n="604" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d604">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5–445: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-04T18:00:00+07:00">May 4, 1945—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 4—11:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>723. Many of the recent editorials in the Chungking press commenting on
                    Sino-Russian relations (Embassy’s 719 [<hi rend="italic">724</hi>], May 3 [<hi rend="italic">4</hi>], 6 [<hi rend="italic">7</hi>] p.m.<note n="26" xml:id="d604fn26">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra.</hi>
                    </note>) are so similar that they appear to have been written under detailed
                    instructions from the Ministry of Information. This tends to substantiate a
                    report from a reliable source that the Ministry of Information has in fact
                    issued a recent directive to the Chinese press to print nothing derogatory to
                    the USSR.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, repeated to Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
